<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>COMMODITY FEARS ADD TO PRESSURE ON SHARES</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Mondayâs <b>sell-off continued into Tuesday</b> with stocks falling across Asia and markets opening lower in Europe. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shares in the Swiss mining and trading firm, Glencore, plunged nearly 30 percent on Monday after the investment bank Investec raised doubts about its valuation, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/reuters/2015/09/28/business/28reuters-markets-stocks-ftse.html"> Reuters reports</a>. Fear then rippled through the markets, pulling the <b>Standard &#038; Poorâs 500-stock index down 2.57 percent</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/29/business/dealbook/investors-fears-on-commodities-add-to-pressure-on-share-prices.html?ref=dealbook&#038;_r=0">Peter Eavis reports in DealBook.</a> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The benchmark is now only marginally above the low that it sank to in August.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Dow Jones industrial average also fell, closing down 1.92 percent. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Much of the weakness in the markets comes from concerns about the strength of the global economy.<br />
<b>Indiaâs central bank</b> cut rates more than expected on Tuesday, reaffirming fears about prospects for global growth, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/30/business/dealbook/asia-markets-nikkei-shanghai-glencore-commodities.html?ref=international">Amie Tsang reports in DealBook</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <b>Problems with big companies</b> are also adding to the bearishness on the economy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Glencoreâs shares are down nearly 90 percent from the price at which they went public in 2011. Trading firms like this depend on constant access to cheap credit to finance their bets, but creditors may cut back their loans to a trading firm if <b>prospects appear to be dimming</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Glencore has tried to strengthen its balance sheet, but its <b>falling shares</b> indicate that investors may be looking for more. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Investors were also trying to assess how much the emissions testing <b>scandal at Volkswagen</b> was likely to affect the auto sector. Biotechnology companies have also been sold off recently, as politicians have expressed frustration with drug prices.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>THE PERILS OF HURRIED SALES OF ILLIQUID ASSETS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Boaz Weinstein, the hedge fund manager famous for betting against the JPMorgan Chase trader known as the âLondon Whale,â is being accused of accounting chicanery. The case could have <b>chilling lessons for investors in certain kinds of illiquid assets</b>,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/29/business/dealbook/the-perils-of-forcing-a-sale-of-illiquid-assets.html?ref=dealbook">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Weinstein is being sued by the Public Sector Pension Investment Board of Canada, formerly the largest investor in his hedge fund, Saba Capital. The pension fund wanted to <b>liquidate its investment</b> in Mr. Weinsteinâs fund this year after he piled up losses over two years. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The pension fund estimated it was owed $500 million and gave Mr. Weinstein <b>less than two months to refund the money</b>.Mr. Weinstein pleaded to be allowed to pay it back in installments, but the pension fund said no. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Weinstein began auctioning the corporate bonds, but only three of nine dealers made bids. The <b>valuations given to the bonds were significantly less</b> than their original value and now the pension fund is claiming in a lawsuit that it got $12 million less than it should have for those illiquid assets. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The lawsuit and the low valuation illustrate an issue that has bubbled up in the last year â a <b>liquidity panic</b> could lead to the next financial crisis. And the potential for crisis isnât restricted to large pension funds and wealthy investors. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Weinsteinâs situation demonstrates the <b>costs of selling illiquid assets in a hurry</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âMutual funds, hedge funds and E.T.F.s are part of the âshadow banking system,â where these modern âbanksâ are not required to maintain reserves or even emergency levels of cash,â William H. Gross, the bond investor, said in a letter to investors this summer. âSince they in effect now are the market, a rush for liquidity on the part of the investing public, whether they be individuals in 401(k)âs or institutional pension funds and insurance companies, would find the âmarketâ selling to itself with the Federal Reserve severely <b>limited in its ability to provide assistance.</b>&#8220;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Stephen A. Schwarzman, co-founder and chairman of the Blackstone Group, has also been anxious that regulations have made it <b>harder for banks to act as intermediaries</b> and buy assets if the markets seize up. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We have yet to see what the courts make of the case, but that could take years and we <b>might see a liquidity crisis</b> â and many more cases like this one â first, says Mr. Sorkin.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>YAHOO TO SPIN OFF ALIBABA STAKE</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Yahoo indicated that it was <b>willing to risk a fight with the government</b> to spin off its stake in Alibaba,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/29/business/dealbook/yahoo-to-go-forward-with-alibaba-stake-spinoff.html?ref=dealbook">Michael J. de la Merced reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It disclosed in a regulatory filing that its board voted to stick with the plan to spin out the companyâs 15 percent stake in Alibaba into a <b>separate publicly traded company</b>. The new company, called Aabaco Holdings, would have a division focusing on small businesses.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Shareholders had pressured Yahoo</b> to pursue the move, arguing that they were rightfully owed the proceeds of any eventual sale. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Internal Revenue Service had <b>declined to rule on whether the transaction would be tax-free</b> and had hinted that it would begin cracking down on such spinoffs. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yahoo will proceed with the plan by the end of the year and <b>could face an audit</b> in several years that would declare the move to be taxable.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The <b>Senate Committee on Finance</b> starts a hearing on the financial and economic challenges in Puerto Rico at 10 a.m. The latest data in the <b>S&#038;P/Case-Shiller Home Price Indices</b> will be released at 9 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>PRIVATE EQUITY RUSHES INTO TROUBLED HOME MORTGAGES</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Private equity and hedge fund firms have bought more than 100,000 <b>troubled mortgages at a discount</b> from banks and federal housing agencies,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/29/business/dealbook/as-banks-retreat-private-equity-rushes-to-buy-troubled-home-mortgages.html?ref=dealbook">Matthew Goldstein reports in DealBook.</a><br />
They have emerged as aggressive liquidators for the remains of the mortgage crisis, as banks have retreated, stung by penalties for bumbled mortgage modifications and foreclosures. But they have drawn criticism. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Housing advocates and lawyers for borrowers say they are <b>too quick to push homes into foreclosure</b>. They also say private equity firms and hedge funds are even less helpful than banks in negotiating loan modifications. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Lone Star Funds, a $60 billion private equity firm, has been criticized despite being admired by investors. Its mortgage servicing firm, Caliber Home Loans, has grown from a bit player to a <b>major force in the market for distressed mortgages</b> in just a few years. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The New York Times examined housing data and court filings and the findings, as well as interviews, reveal complaints that Lone Star has been <b>quick to begin foreclosure proceedings</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Caliber said it had one of the <b>highest loan modification rates</b> in the industry. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In 2014, Lone Star bought a bundle of 17,000 distressed mortgages with an unpaid balance of $2.96 billion. Department of Housing and Urban Development rules barred Lone Star from foreclosing on most of the mortgages until early March, but the <b>pace of foreclosures since then has picked up</b>. By the end of August, Lone Star and Caliber had foreclosed on at least 1,500 of these mortgages, or 9 percent of the pool. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A majority of the homes foreclosed on by Caliber have been bought back by another Lone Star affiliate at either a trustee or sheriffâs auction. The private equity firm is <b>looking to resell the homes</b>, and many can be found on an online real estate listing service.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Other firms, like Bayview Asset Management, a Blackstone Group affiliate, and Selene Investment Partners, have swarmed into troubled mortgages. They squeeze profits from them either by restructuring or foreclosing on them and then <b>repackaging the distressed loans into bonds</b> that are sold to mutual funds and hedge funds. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The move has produced some benefits. Thousands of homes abandoned by borrowers are back on the market. But housing advocates argue for <b>giving nonprofits a better chance of competing</b> for these mortgages as they are likely to work harder to avoid foreclosures. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>HUD has responded</b> by increasing the period during which a private buyer cannot foreclose on homes, and has sought to create smaller pools of loans to give nonprofits a better chance at submitting winning bids.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
</div>
